Ellen Hoffman
4.0 out of 5 stars Why We Can't Have Nice Things
Reviewed in the United States on December 22, 2022
Verified Purchase
I was disproportionately inflamed upon receiving this keyboard and using it for the first few hours because of the reviews I had read about this keyboard, living under the shadow of the now extinct 4000 keyboard. The keys were factory slick (like actually slippery), impossibly small for my King James hands, and I did actually encounter several of these missed keys others have mentioned.

However, you'll be pleased to hear that on behalf of my incredibly dry african hands, I have managed to shave off the smooth keys and I genuinely feel some normalcy typing as I long for what we can no longer purchase. Truly, this keyboard is not as good as the GOAT msft 4000 keyboard, but it is a... somewhat worthy successor. It feels very good, from an ergo perspective, and with time, you do get used to some of the aggravating aspects of this keyboard, mainly the tiny keys which are also smashed together, most notably the F keys. You will enjoy disabling random elements of software and spend hours wondering what key you hit.

Perhaps the designer envisioned excellent world where we are no longer intimidated by buttons that must be hit precisely, in the event that an alien race appears in our world with fascinating new puzzles that threaten our way of life if we do not finish sequences with compete accuracy. IDK

Nevertheless, if there were a world where amazing products suddenly snapped out of existence and were replaced with husks of their former selves, it would be this keyboard. Oh, right. That is this world.
